e":"LAST","meanings":["A Welsh name. Some write the name Hoel, which they render 'lordly;' if so, it may come from huail, a vice-regent, regent. Arthur derives the surname Howell from Corn. -Brit, houl, the sun; and he adds, high, exalted.' But Hywel is rather from hywel, conspicuous."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Dafydd","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>David</b> . In widespread use during the Middle Ages, it was later largely replaced by the English form, but since the late 19th century it has come into its own again."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Melyn","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of uncertain origin, possibly from Latin <i>Aemilianus</i> (a derivative of the old Roman family name <i>Aemilius</i>, which is probably from <i>aemulus</i> ‘rival’). Alternatively, it may have a Celtic origin; there are Breton and Irish saints recorded as <i>Aemilianus</i>, which may be a Latinized form of a lost Celtic name."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Dafydd Melyn ap Hywel was born in Cantref, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom as the son of Hywel ap Jenkin and Elen Banw. He married Gwenllian Ferch Rhys in Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1390–1450":"1390–1450","–Male":"Surnud","1387–Female":"1387–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1408–Female":"1408–Surnud","1420–Female":"1420–Surnud","1410–Male":"1410–Surnud","about 1408":"umbes 1408","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1387":"1387","1450":"1450","about 1420":"umbes 1420","1408":"1408","1390":"1390","Cemaes, Pembrokeshire,Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales","of Hirfryn,Cantref Bychan,Carmarthenshire,Wales":"Cantref, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Llangedwyn, Denbighshire, Wales":"Llangedwyn, Denbighshire, Wales"},